<div class="jm-page-hero">
  <h1>About JustMadness</h1>
  <p>The philosophy behind the madness.</p>
</div>

<div class="section">
  <div class="section-inner">
    <div class="badge">Who I am</div>
    <h2>The best parties don't need an entertainer.<br>They need a good enough story.</h2>
    <p>I'm a mum. I've spent years planning my daughter's birthday parties — properly planning them, way more than was probably necessary.</p>
    <p>It started with her first big party at a soft play centre. Two hours later it was over — the kids had descended like a swarm of grasshoppers and vanished just as fast, leaving nothing but crumbs and chaos. I remember looking at her afterwards thinking: I'm not sure she even knew this was her party. Nothing about it was bad, exactly. It just wasn't hers.</p>

    <h3>Looking for something better</h3>
    <p>So I went looking for something that actually felt like it belonged to her. Not another room full of borrowed activities — something with a story in it, that the kids could get properly lost in.</p>
    <p>Everything I found was either a party company charging a fortune for something generic, or a printable pack with clues that led nowhere and called itself a treasure hunt. Neither one was it. So I started making it myself.</p>

    <h3>What the children taught me</h3>
    <p>The thing that taught me most wasn't my planning — it was watching the kids play. They'd tell me straight away, without meaning to, what was boring, what confused them, what made them forget they were even at a party because they were too busy trying to save the day. Every mission got better because of them, not because of me.</p>

    <div class="highlight">JustMadness isn't just for birthdays. Family gatherings, BBQs, school holidays, a rainy Sunday with cousins — anything where you'd rather the kids disappear into a mission than disappear behind a screen.<br><br>I built it because I couldn't find the party I wanted to give my daughter. I hope it gives your children a party worth talking about.</div>
  </div>
</div>

